'''Andrew Brackman''' (born , ) is a 6' 10"    with the  organization.<ref>[http://www.minorleaguebaseball.com/milb/events/draft_report/y2007/index.jsp?mc=brackman Draft Report for Andrew Brackman]</ref> He signed a four year $4.55 million dollar deal with $3.35 million signing bonus as the 30th overall pick of the .<ref name=CSTV.com>{{cite news
Brackman attended  in .  There he was one of the top high school pitchers in the country, and a two-sport standout.  He had a career ERA of 1.04, the seventh best in the history of Ohio high school baseball,<ref name=MLB.com>
He was runner-up for Mr. Basketball in Ohio by the , shared Ohio's Division I Player of the Year honors, and was named first-team all-state, as he averaged 20.2 points and 6.5 rebounds as a senior.  He led his conference in scoring and field-goal percentage (.654), and was second in free-throw percentage (.882).  He was rated the No. 42 prospect nationally by Insiders.com, and No. 43 by PrepStars following his senior season.<ref name=GoPack.com>
He then attended and played at .  Brackman played two seasons as a dual-sport athlete at NC State, playing both basketball and baseball. During his freshman year basketball season (2004-2005), he played center and forward averaging 7.4 points and 3.5 rebounds.<ref name=CBS>
In his freshman baseball season, he was 4-0 with a 2.09 ERA in 10 appearances as both a reliever and later, a starting pitcher.  He was starting pitcher of the first game of the , striking out five batters in seven innings to earn the victory against the .  He was named a second-team preseason All-America player by  for .  <ref name=GoPack.com>
After the  was knocked out of the , in the second round by Texas, Brackman chose not to return to the basketball team the next season and instead to develop his pitching with hopes of doing well in professional baseball.  
Brackman suffered a  stress fracture to his hip in his sophomore year basketball season limiting him to only 7 games and a disappointing 1-4 record with a 6.09 ERA.<ref name=ESPN>
Brackman's junior year at NC State saw a return to his freshman year numbers: in 13 games, he struck out 74 batters in 78 innings with a 3.81 ERA and a record of 6-4.  He did not pitch in the ACC nor the NCAA tournaments due to elbow injuries.<ref name=NewYorkPost>
Despite anxiety about the effect of his past injuries on his draft stock, Brackman did well in the , drafted by the Yankees with the 30th pick of the first round<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/events/draft/y2007/drafttracker.jsp 2007 MLB.com Draft tracker]</ref>.
Following the 2007 draft, the Yankees signed Brackman to a guaranteed $4.5 million deal for four years including a $3.55 million signing bonus spread out over six years.<ref name=NewYorkTimes>
As specified by his contract on August 15, 2007, the Yankees placed Brackman on the 40 man roster (designating   for assignment to make room for him).<ref name=CSTV.com>{{cite news
Brackman was optioned to the Class-A  in the .  The Yankees recommended that Brackman see  in Alabama to address his lingering elbow concerns.  Later in August 2007, he underwent .<ref name=NewYorkPost>
Brackman began the 2008 season on the 60 day disabled list, a procedural move to keep him on the 40-man roster. He's not expected to pitch until the very end of the year, when he'll begin preparing for a spring 2009 start. Despite this setback, the Yankees still consider Brackman a "blue-chip prospect".<ref name=NewYorkDailyNews>{{cite news
